<paragraph id="0DBF968EF164614D0050DE7E663EF155" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5CB653599537FB501EB301934580B380" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">
AFGHANISTAN, 
<emphasis id="1B6AB6922B1EFF6CB3418471D30CD136" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Lindberg</emphasis>
317 (holotype W!).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DF523B1F13899DA6C4EF7CB832EC231C" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" type="distinguishing features">
<paragraph id="3D1BD63685F69E676B51C45078CD765C" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Distinguishing features.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B2A14E68E1FF509FB23DA1485F33B755" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">
This differs from 
<taxonomicName id="D7B2010FEDDED912ECD567CC399C2FE8" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="subsp. var. var. leiocalycinus" order="Solanales" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="retrosepalus" subSpecies="var." variety="leiocalycinus">var. leiocalycinus</taxonomicName>
by the narrowly lanceolate, reflexed sepals, c. 7 
<normalizedToken id="85C23BAF8474A4019736AF3E1EB800CA" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1 mm, the veins usually conspicuous. The leaves and ovary are glabrous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7E913C718CBF9E2AF2848E4BEA98AD8F" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="E2BB08C844490A8BD67F66DB485CF941" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="03E5809C67E515BE712A71C3FD2DFA30" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">
Restricted to Afghanistan, Farah Province (
<emphasis id="2FB05D142CCFE034D09D0699C3B91E09" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Hedge &amp; Ekberg</emphasis>
7252, 
<emphasis id="8CFE097270FA554D3FBE4B688EC0DD7D" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Hedge et al.</emphasis>
7739, 
<emphasis id="E304EF3318E2892A6CA589BDF2D54FCC" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Grey-Wilson &amp; Hewer</emphasis>
557, 
<emphasis id="92F9DE2FA17EAFCFA4422B1FA8C622BF" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Carter</emphasis>
824).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="63B2E049BFFCB12307CADB0B9C915A44" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" type="note">
<paragraph id="7AFB6F769F5776A9E0D127E3D70EA82D" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E48C541D8A0B11104109FF7D72A401CB" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">
Intermediates with 
<taxonomicName id="52D469309459BCF7EB118F3CB5B95657" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="subsp. var. var. leiocalycinus" order="Solanales" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="retrosepalus" subSpecies="var." variety="leiocalycinus">var. leiocalycinus</taxonomicName>
occur quite frequently (
<emphasis id="B105CEF90A8DC888E416A1FFAE1CC82B" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Grey-Wilson &amp; Hewer</emphasis>
534, 
<emphasis id="D92BFBA5DBE8473693D2DE634DEE3E6F" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Podlech</emphasis>
21729, 
<emphasis id="8FA1DD4B7FA14B51D65338BD0908F108" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Rechinger</emphasis>
33380, 
<emphasis id="A5B3CE368D7B386642E22B5FBA90821F" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Koie</emphasis>
4414). These are similar to 
<taxonomicName id="2908D524EB1598605F38B6E197E68A87" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="subsp. var. var. retrosepalus" order="Solanales" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="retrosepalus" subSpecies="var." variety="retrosepalus">var. retrosepalus</taxonomicName>
in their lack of hairs but the sepals are obovate and spreading.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
